SIMPLE: imply
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Imply
<hw>Im*ply"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Implied</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Implying</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[From the same source as employ.
See <er>Employ</er>, <er>Ply</er>, and cf. <er>Implicate</er>,
<er>Apply</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To infold or involve; to wrap
up.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧His head in curls
<xex>implied</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Chapman.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To involve in substance or essence, or by fair
inference, or by construction of law, when not include virtually;
<as>as, war <ex>implies</ex> fighting</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Where a malicious act is proved, a malicious intention is
<qex>implied</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Bp. Sherlock.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When a man employs a laborer to work for him, . . . the act of
hiring <qex>implies</qex> an obligation and a promise that he shall pay
him a reasonable reward for his services.</q>
<rj><qau>Blackstone.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To refer, ascribe, or attribute.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whence might this distaste arise?</q>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If [from] neither your perverse and peevish will.⟦br⟧
To which I most <qex>imply</qex> it.</q> <rj><qau>J.
Webster.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To involve; include; comprise; import; mean;
denote; signify; betoken. See <er>Involve</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Impoison</ent>⟦br⟧
